findings.reasoning: The finding identifies a front-running vulnerability where an attacker could deploy to the same address. However, this is not the actual vulnerability. The ground truth identifies a DOS issue where the function reverts with CreateCollision instead of returning the existing address per ERC-4337 expectations. The finding's suggested fix (including msg.sender in salt) would actually break the intended counterfactual deployment pattern and doesn't address the root cause of the revert behavior. The finding mischaracterizes the issue as a front-running/griefing problem when the real issue is the violation of ERC-4337 expectations and improper handling of existing deployments.

notes: The finding correctly identifies the deploy function but completely misses the actual vulnerability. The ground truth describes a DOS issue due to revert on collision instead of returning the address. The finding describes a front-running issue and suggests a fix that would prevent counterfactual deployments. This is a classic case of identifying a different issue in the same function.
